From the above information retreived about 'Center for World University Rankings' Data,we can clearly see that there are no missing values in any of the attributes except in the attribute named 'broad_impact' which has 200 rows having NaNs.Apart from this issue,all the attributes are having appropriate data types in accordance with data they contain.

Therefore,there is a need to perform 'Data Cleansing' step to handle missing values in 'broad_impact'.

Data Cleansing/Data Preparation Steps¶

We need to prepare data in 'broad_impact' feature by replacing or imputing NaNs/Nulls by average value for this attribute across years for a particular university.We will further replace still remaining Null or NaN with 0 for those institutions which have NaNs/Null across years.

In [13]:
df['broad_impact']=df['broad_impact'].fillna(df.groupby(['institution'])['broad_impact'].transform('mean'))
df['broad_impact']=df['broad_impact'].fillna(0)

def answer_four():
    df = pd.read_csv("cwurData.csv")
    df.head()
    X_Reg = df['publications'].values
    Y_Target = df['world_rank'].values
    X_Reg = X_Reg.reshape(len(X_Reg),1)
    Y_Target= Y_Target.reshape(len(Y_Target),1)
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X_Reg, Y_Target, test_size=0.3, random_state=0)
    regressor = LinearRegression()
    regressor.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    print('Coefficient:' , regressor.coef_)
    print('Intercept:' , regressor.intercept_)
    Y_Pred = regressor.predict(X_test)
    print('Linear Regression R squared: %.2f' % regressor.score(X_test, Y_test))
    mse = mean_squared_error(Y_Pred, Y_test)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
    print('Linear Regression RMSE: %.2f' % rmse)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(Y_Pred, Y_test)
    print('Linear Regression MAE: %.2f' % mae)
    plt.scatter(X_train, Y_train)
    plt.plot(X_test, Y_Pred, color='magenta')
    plt.show()
    return None
answer_four()
